  "style": "",
  "texts": [
    "The literature on bias in machine learning (Mehrabi et al., 2021; Suresh & Guttag, 2021a, 2021b) focuses on seven sources of bias that are particularly relevant in the AI scoring context: historical bias, representation bias, measurement bias, aggregation bias, learning/algorithmic bias, evaluation bias, and deployment bias.",
    "For example, the features used as part of the model may contribute additional biases if they carry construct irrelevant variance for some subgroups (Johnson & McCaffrey, 2023).",
    "Therefore, it is crucial to choose a model and features that best represent the task for the construct at hand and minimize construct irrelevance for all groups.",
    "Importantly, these various sources of bias could affect fairness in different ways.",
    "Recent literature (Johnson & McCaffrey, 2023) provides a nuanced conceptualization of fairness: AI scores can have independence (scores are independent of group membership such as whether language group), separation fairness (conditionally independent of group membership, given the true score), sufficiency fairness (true score is conditionally independent of the group membership given the AI score), and/or conditional unbiasedness (i.e., test takers are not negatively affected by the use of machine scores or human ratings)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}